## Interpreting the fit

At distance `x`, the average count is `≈ exp(2.4 - 0.5x)`

- `x = 0` $\implies$ `exp(2.4) ≈ 11.0`
- `x = 0.5` $\implies$ `exp(2.4 − 0.5 × 3.9) ≈ 1.6`


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](slides_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-15-1.png){width=960}
:::
:::


## Overdispersion

Often unmeasured factors influence the rates, making the data more heterogeneous than the Poisson can handle.

   - E.g., infection might depend not only on distance but on unknown, county-specific population densities.

The **negative binomial** addresses this — it arises as a mixture of Poissons with similar but slightly different rates.

## Negative binomial data


::: {.cell}

:::



::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](slides_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-17-1.png){width=768}
:::
:::


The blue mean line is unchanged, but counts at a given distance are more spread out.

## Fitting with `glm.nb`

`glm` doesn't have a negative binomial model, but `glm.nb` from the **MASS**
package does. The syntax is the same as before.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
fit <- glm.nb(infected ~ epicenter_distance, data = outbreak_nb)
modelsummary(fit, shape = term ~ statistic, gof_map = NA)
```

