## Why Gaussian errors?

The **Central Limit Theorem**: the average of many small, independent effects tends toward a Gaussian distribution.

We implicitly assume many small, independent factors other than age that perturb the observed antibody measurement.

[picture of gsn errors around regression line]

## Survival Models

Survival models describe **whether and when an event occurs**.

- Time until heart attack
- Time until loan default
- Time until HIV acquisition


If the event doesn't happen during the study, the participant's response is called **censored**.

## The outcome has *two* parts

Unlike the other models, the survival outcome is *two* numbers:

::: incremental
- `time` — when the event was observed (or the study ended)
- `status` — whether the event happened (`1`) or was censored (`0`)
:::

## Example: HIV acquisition

A hypothetical two-year study tracking participants on drug vs. control. Some
have an event (triangles), the rest are censored.


::: {.cell}

:::



::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](slides_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-23-1.png){width=912}
:::
:::


## The Cox proportional hazards model

The Cox PH model is the most popular survival model.

- During any time interval, anyone who hasn't yet had an event is **at risk**.
- Covariates can change the relative risk (the **"hazard"**) of the event.
- A covariate shifts the hazard by the same factor at all times → *proportional* hazards.

[picture for intuition]

## Fitting `coxph`


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
fit <- coxph(Surv(time, status) ~ treatment, data = surv_data)
modelsummary(fit, shape = term ~ statistic, gof_map = NA)
```

